docs.lead_paragraph: Stage rarities are not really that rare on the New York stage. The Bicentennial year turned up a number of Early American plays, and not too long ago, Broadway was host to Dion Boucicault's "London Assurance" and William Gillette's old chestnut, "Sherlock Holmes." But tonight the Jean Cocteau Repertory will unveil a genuine rarity at the Bouwerie Lane Theater when it presents Percy Bysshe Shelley's verse drama "The Cenci."

docs.lead_paragraph: Someone is practicing a scale in the foyer. It is part bell-like soprano, part fire-siren wail. The vocalist, a small, round-faced woman in her 40's, waits by the door. She is possessed, as Clive Barnes once put it, of a certain "batbered friendly charm." Her anklelength, flowered cotton skirt is faded and her lavender T-shirt is full of discreet but hardly unnoticable holes.
